# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nft-tokens
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The **ERC-721 Non-fungible Token Standard** is a technical framework, defining a set of rules and interfaces for creating and managing unique, non-fungible tokens (NFTs) on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] ERC-721 is recognized for formalizing the concept of an NFT and establishing the foundation of the multi-billion dollar digital collectibles ecosystem that emerged alongside its adoption.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] It is one of the most widely used NFT standards across use cases and has been utilized in various high profile projects.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The development of the standard was a community-driven effort that was formally published into a paper of the same name in 2018 and is accredited to William Entriken and co-authors Dieter Shirley, Jacob Evans, and Nastassia Sachs.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] ERC stands for "Ethereum Request for Comments," and is a part of the Ethereum community's peer-review process in which new proposals are considered for publication; the "721" is a unique identifier, each proposal is assigned one arbitrarily after an editor approves it in the draft phase.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The blockchain game featuring digital cat artworks known as *CryptoKitties* is credited with pioneering ERC-721 when it achieved mainstream attention shortly after its launch in 2017.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The concept of non-fungible digital assets that could be owned on a blockchain predated ERC-721, with projects like Colored Coins on Bitcoin in 2012.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] In 2017, just prior to ERC-721’s publication, Larva Labs launched the *CryptoPunks* NFT project on Ethereum using ERC-20 (a fungible token standard).
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] *CryptoPunks* served as a direct inspiration for ERC-721’s initial drafting.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The term "non-fungible token" (NFT) is not known to have been used to refer to NFT projects prior to ERC-721.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard* is credited with formalizing and defining the term NFT.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] During the standard's drafting phase, lead author Entriken held a vote among the stakeholders where different words were considered including deed, title and asset, but ultimately "NFT" was chosen for the standard's final publication.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Use of the term's popularity grew through *CryptoKitties,* the blockchain game featuring digital cats NFT utilizing ERC-721.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The blockchain game *CryptoKitties* by Dapper Labs of which the CTO Dieter Shirley is a fellow co-author of ERC-721, is recognized as the earliest pioneering and popular instance of the ERC-721 standard.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] It utilized an early version of ERC-721 that was not fully compliant with the standard published in 2018.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] *CryptoKitties* is regarded as among the first NFT applications to achieve widespread adoption, earning millions of dollars initially and taking up to 70% of Ethereum's usage capacity at its height in some moments.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Launched in 2018 by Entriken and inspired by the Million Dollar Homepage, this NFT project is the first fully compliant demonstration of the ERC-721 NFT standard.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] In 2017, one of the earliest and most successful NFT marketplaces, OpenSea, was launched by co-founders Alex Atallah and Devin Finzer who intended to capitalize off of the emergence of ERC-721 NFTs on Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] They initially focused on capturing the market activity around the blockchain NFT game *CryptoKitties*, which was one of the first use cases of ERC-721, and ultimately planned to scale the platform for other emerging projects utilizing it.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The NFT marketplace SuperRare also emerged in 2018 to enable trading of tokens of this standard.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] ERC-721 implementation requires "name" and "symbol" identifiers, and the token is assigned a contract address upon deployment to the blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Also, a mechanism to implement a URI (Uniform Resource Identifier) to the contract, is defined in the standard, providing functionality to assign each NFT unique metadata.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Though not required, most NFTs implementing ERC-721 will also implement the OpenSea Metadata Standard.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Trackable ownership is the key feature which adds non-fungibility to the ERC-721 standard.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Each NFT is assigned a token identification number, and linked to its owner through the "ownerOf" function.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Through the optional "ERC-721 Enumerable" extension, functionality for full ownership tracking is implemented.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] This differs from the ERC-20 token standard, which only tracks an owners token balance though ERC-721 also tracks it as well.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The ERC-721 standard defines both safe and unsafe transfer functions, offering different levels of security for various implementations.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] These functions allow transfers initiated by the token owner, or an approved operator of their individual tokens.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Further, developers can implement custom logic to these transfer functions, providing the functionality for NFT protocols to operate.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] For example, marketplaces like OpenSea, make use of approved operators to facilitate the sale of NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The influence of the paper *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard* that Entriken lead authorship of spans across various sectors, profoundly shaping the landscape of digital collectibles and the use cases within the broader NFT eco-system.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] ERC-721 was awarded rank #1 in *ArtReview's Power 100* in 2021 indicating it as "the most powerful art entity in the world" and being the first non-human entity to be ranked as such.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Several months after *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard* was published, a semi-fungible token standard was introduced, called ERC-1155, that was intended to expand on the functionality and flexibility of ERC-721's purpose.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The same ERC-721 standard is utilized on the Polygon blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Other standards have proposed extensions or alternatives to ERC-721 for specific NFT use cases.
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] ERC-7160, finalized in 2023, extends ERC-721 metadata by allowing multiple metadata URIs per token.*"ERC-7160: ERC-721 Multi-Metadata Extension".
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] Retrieved 11 June 2026.* ERC-725 defines generic data storage and execution interfaces that can be used to enhance NFT and token metadata.*"ERC-725: General data key/value store and execution".
[src:nft-tokens/erc-721] The basic version of the ERC-721 standard, as published in *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard*, has been criticized by *Omar et al* for offering limited functionality for the execution of smart contracts associated with NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:nft-tokens/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] A **non-fungible token** (**NFT**) is a unique digital identifier that is recorded on a blockchain and is used to certify ownership and authenticity.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] They typically contain references to digital files such as artworks, photos, videos, and audio.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Because NFTs are uniquely identifiable, they differ from cryptocurrencies (which are fungible, hence the name non-fungible token), and as a result they cannot be copied, substituted, or subdivided.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Their ownership can be transferred by the owner, allowing NFTs to be sold and traded.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Initially pitched in 2017 as a new class of investment asset, NFT trading increased from US$82 million in 2020 to US$17 billion in 2021.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Its market was occasionally compared to an economic bubble or a Ponzi scheme.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In 2022, the NFT market collapsed; a May 2022 estimate was that the number of sales was down over 90% compared to 2021.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] By September 2023 one report claimed that over 95% of NFT collections had zero monetary value.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Proponents claim that NFTs provide a public certificate of authenticity or proof of ownership, but the legal rights conveyed by an NFT can be uncertain.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The ownership of an NFT as defined by the blockchain has no inherent legal meaning and does not necessarily grant copyright, intellectual property rights, or other legal rights over its associated digital file.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] An NFT does not restrict the sharing or copying of its associated digital file and does not prevent the creation of NFTs that reference identical files.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs have been used as speculative investments and have drawn criticism for the energy cost and carbon footprint associated with some types of blockchain, as well as their use in art scams.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] An NFT is a data file, stored on a type of digital ledger called a blockchain, which can be sold and traded.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The NFT can be associated with a particular asset – digital or physical – such as an image, art, music, or recording of a sports event.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] It may confer licensing rights to use the asset for a specified purpose.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] An NFT (and, if applicable, the associated license to use, copy, or display the underlying asset) can be traded and sold on digital markets.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] However, the extralegal nature of NFT trading usually results in an informal exchange of ownership over the asset that has no legal basis for enforcement, and so often confers little more than use as a status symbol.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs function like cryptographic tokens, but unlike cryptocurrencies, NFTs are not usually mutually interchangeable, so they are not fungible.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] A non-fungible token contains data links, for example which point to details about where the associated art is stored, that can be affected by link rot.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] An NFT solely represents a proof of ownership of a blockchain record and does not necessarily imply that the owner possesses intellectual property rights to the digital asset the NFT purports to represent.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Someone may sell an NFT that represents their work, but the buyer will not necessarily receive copyright to that work, and the seller may not be prohibited from creating additional NFT copies of the same work.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] According to legal scholar Rebecca Tushnet, "In one sense, the purchaser acquires whatever the art world thinks they have acquired.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Certain NFT projects, such as Bored Apes, explicitly assign intellectual property rights of individual images to their respective owners.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The NFT collection CryptoPunks was a project that initially prohibited owners of its NFTs from using the associated digital artwork for commercial use, but later allowed such use upon acquisition by the collection's parent company.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The first known NFT, *Quantum*, was created by Kevin McCoy and Anil Dash in May 2014.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] It consists of a video clip made by McCoy's wife, Jennifer.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] McCoy registered the video on the Namecoin blockchain and sold it to Dash for $4, during a live presentation for the *Seven on Seven* conferences at the New Museum in New York City.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] McCoy and Dash referred to the technology as "monetized graphics".
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] This explicitly linked a non-fungible, tradable blockchain marker to a work of art, via on-chain metadata (enabled by Namecoin).
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In October 2015, Etheria, was launched and demonstrated at DEVCON 1 in London, Ethereum's first developer conference, three months after the launch of the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Most of Etheria's 457 purchasable and tradable hexagonal tiles went unsold for more than five years until March 13, 2021, when renewed interest in NFTs sparked a buying frenzy.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Within 24 hours, all tiles of the current version and a prior version, each hardcoded to 1 ETH (US$0.43 at the time of launch) were sold for a total of US$1.4 million.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In 2017, several NFT projects emerged on Ethereum that utilized a "fungible" token standard known as ERC-20.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] *Curio Cards* in May of that year is credited with being Ethereum's first art NFT project using the fungible standard and features artwork in the shape of a card among a variety of image types, including satirized corporate logos.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The generative art project of 10,000 pixelated characters known as *CryptoPunks* emerged soon after in June and would later establish itself as one of the most commercially successful NFT projects.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In December, a clipart based collection featuring images of rocks called *EtherRock* emerged.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In November 2017, the widely acclaimed blockchain game on Ethereum known as *CryptoKitties* launched, and is credited with pioneering what is considered to be the first bona fide non-fungible token standard, known as ERC-721.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] It used an early version of ERC-721 that differed from the formally published version of the standard in 2018.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] It introduced the formalization and defining of the term *Non-Fungible Token* "NFT" in blockchain nomenclature by establishing a standard for smart contracts known as "ERC-721" whose tokens would have unique attributes and ownership details, ensuring no two tokens are alike.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The creation of derivative standards followed from its influence on Ethereum (like ERC-1155 enabling semi-fungibility) and other blockchains.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Its versatility enabled the pioneering of numerous use cases, including digital artwork, deeds to physical items, real estate (including virtual), access passes, and game assets.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Ultimately, the emergence of ERC-721 is recognized for having fundamentally changed the landscape of digital verification, authentication, and ownership.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The term NFT, prior to the blockchain game *CryptoKitties'* adoption of ERC-721, is not known to have been used for earlier projects.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The term "NFT" and the awareness of the ERC-721 standard received significant exposure and adopted use through the popularity of *CryptoKitties* in 2017.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] While using the standard, *CryptoKitties* earned the recognition of being the first mainstream NFT dApp; the game's usage was significant enough to have overwhelmed Ethereum's processing power at the time.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] During the height of the breakout success of *CryptoKitties* and the emergence of ERC-721 tokens in 2017, an NFT marketplace called OpenSea emerged to capitalize off of the new non-fungible token standard.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] It positioned itself early in the NFT market landscape and grew to a $1.4 billion market cap in 2021 during the then-ongoing NFT boom.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In 2021, *ArtReview's Power 100* ranked ERC-721 at the #1 spot, praising it as "the most powerful art entity in the world" for creating a new kind of market for artworks that deviated from traditional gatekeeping norms and ushered in a different kind of collector.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Artist Beeple sold an ERC-721 NFT of his composite artwork known as *Everydays: the First 5000 Days* at Christie's for $69 million and was the first instance of a legacy arthouse dealing in NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The NFT market experienced rapid growth during 2020, with its value tripling to US$250 million.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In the first three months of 2021, more than US$200 million were spent on NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In the early months of 2021, interest in NFTs increased after a number of high-profile sales and art auctions.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In May 2022, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that the NFT market was "collapsing".
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Daily sales of NFT tokens had declined 92% from September 2021, and the number of active wallets in the NFT market fell 88% from November 2021.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In December 2022, a programmer named Casey Rodarmor introduced a new way to add NFTs to the Bitcoin blockchain called "ordinals".
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] By February 2023, the popularity of ordinals had led to an increase in bitcoin's payment fees and may have also partially contributed to an increase in bitcoin's price.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] A September 2023 report from cryptocurrency gambling website dappGambl claimed 95% of NFTs had fallen to zero monetary value and 79% of all NFT collections have remained unsold.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs have been used to exchange digital tokens that link to a digital file asset.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Ownership of an NFT is often associated with a license to use such a linked digital asset but generally does not confer the copyright to the buyer.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Some agreements only grant a license for personal, non-commercial use, while other licenses also allow commercial use of the underlying digital asset.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] This kind of decentralized intellectual copyright poses an alternative to established forms of safeguarding copyright controlled by state institutions and middlemen within the respective industry.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Digital art is a common use case for NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] High-profile auctions of NFTs linked to digital art have received considerable public attention; the first such major house auction took place at Christie's in 2021.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The work entitled *Merge* by artist Pak was the most expensive NFT, with an auction price of US$91.8 million and *Everydays: the First 5000 Days*, by artist Mike Winkelmann (known professionally as Beeple) the second most expensive at US$69.3 million in 2021.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Some NFT collections, including Bored Apes, EtherRocks, and CryptoPunks, are examples of generative art, where many different images are created by assembling a selection of simple picture components in different combinations.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In March 2021, the blockchain company Injective Protocol bought a $95,000 original screen print entitled *Morons (White)* from English graffiti artist Banksy and filmed somebody burning it with a cigarette lighter.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] They uploaded (known as "minting" in the NFT scene) and sold the video as an NFT.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The person who destroyed the artwork, who called themselves "Burnt Banksy", described the act as a way to transfer a physical work of art to the NFT space.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] American curator and art historian Tina Rivers Ryan, who specializes in digital works, said that art museums are widely not convinced that NFTs have "lasting cultural relevance." Ryan compares NFTs to the net art fad before the dot-com bubble.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In July 2022, after the controversial sale of Michelangelo's *Doni Tondo* in Italy, the sale of NFT reproductions of famous artworks was prohibited in Italy.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Given the complexity and lack of regulation of the matter, the Ministry of Culture of Italy temporarily requested that its institutions refrain from signing contracts involving NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs associated with digital artworks could be sold and bought via NFT platforms.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] OpenSea, launched in 2017, was one of the first marketplaces to host various types of NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In July 2019, the National Basketball Association, the NBA Players Association and Dapper Labs, the creator of CryptoKitties, started a joint venture NBA Top Shot for basketball fans that let users buy NFTs of historic moments in basketball.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In 2020, Rarible was found, allowing multiple assets.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In 2021, Rarible and Adobe formed a partnership to simplify the verification and security of metadata for digital content, including NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In 2021, a cryptocurrency exchange Binance, launched its NFT marketplace.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In 2022, eToro Art by eToro was founded, focusing on supporting NFT collections and emerging creators.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Sotheby's and Christie's auction houses showcase artworks associated with the respective NFTs both in virtual galleries and physical screens, monitors, and TVs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Mars House, an architectural NFT created in May 2020 by artist Krista Kim, sold in 2021 for 288 Ether (ETH) — at that time equivalent to US$524,558.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Some commentators describe these as being controlled "by the user" instead of the game developer if they can be traded on third-party marketplaces without permission from the game developer.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Their reception from game developers, though, has been generally mixed, with some like Ubisoft embracing the technology but Valve and Microsoft formally prohibiting them.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs have been proposed for use within the film-industry as a way to tokenize movie-scenes and sell them as collectibles in the form of NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Artists involved in the entertainment-industry can seek royalties through NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] So far, NFTs have often been used in both the music- as well as the film-industry.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] By February 2021, NFTs accounted for US$25 million of revenue generated through the sale of artwork and songs as NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] On February 28, 2021, electronic dance musician 3lau sold a collection of 33 NFTs for a total of US$11.7 million to commemorate the three-year anniversary of his *Ultraviolet* album.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] On March 3, 2021, an NFT was made to promote the Kings of Leon album *When You See Yourself.* Other musicians who have used NFTs include American rapper Lil Pump, Grimes, visual artist Shepard Fairey in collaboration with record producer Mike Dean, and rapper Eminem.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] A paper presented at the *40th International Conference on Information Systems* in Munich in 2019 suggested using NFTs as tickets for different types of events.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] This would enable organizers of the respective events or artists performing there to receive royalties on the resale of each ticket.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs have been proposed for purposes related to scientific and medical purposes.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Suggestions include turning patient data into NFTs, tracking supply chains and minting patents as NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The monetary aspect of the sale of NFTs has been used by academic institutions to finance research projects.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs representing digital collectables and artworks are a speculative asset.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The NFT buying surge was called an economic bubble by experts, who also compared it to the Dot-com bubble.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In March 2021 Mike Winkelmann called NFTs an "irrational exuberance bubble".
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] By mid-April 2021, demand subsided, causing prices to fall significantly.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Bernstein compared the NFT market to 17th-century tulip mania, saying any speculative bubble requires a technological advance for people to "get excited about", with part of that enthusiasm coming from the extreme predictions being made about the product.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] For regulatory policymakers, NFTs have exacerbated challenges such as speculation, fraud, and high volatility.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs, as with other blockchain securities and with traditional art sales, can potentially be used for money laundering.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs can be used for wash trading by creating several wallets for one individual, generating several fictitious sales and consequently selling the respective NFT to a third party.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] According to a report by Chainalysis these types of wash trades are becoming popular among money launderers because of the largely anonymous nature of transactions on NFT marketplaces.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] *Looksrare*, created in early 2022, came to be known for the large sums generated through the sale of NFTs in its earliest days, amounting to US$400,000,000 a day.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] These large sums were generated in large part through wash trading.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The Royal United Services Institute said that any risks in relation to money laundering through NFTs could be mitigated through the use of "KYC best practices, strong cyber security measures and a stolen art registry (...) without restricting the growth of this new market".
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Auction platforms for NFTs may face regulatory pressure to comply with anti-money laundering legislation.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Gou Wenjun, the director of a monitoring centre for the People's Bank of China, said that NFTs could "easily become money-laundering tools".
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] He pointed to unlawful exploitation of cryptographic technologies and said that illicit actors often presented themselves as innovators in financial technology.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] A 2022 study from the United States Treasury assessed that there was "some evidence of money laundering risk in the high-value art market", including through "the emerging digital art market, such as the use of non-fungible tokens (NFTs)".
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The study considered how NFT transactions may be a simpler option for laundering money through art by avoiding the transportation or insurance complications in trading physical art.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Several NFT exchanges were labeled as virtual asset service providers that may be subject to Financial Crimes Enforcement Network regulations.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In March 2022, two people were charged for the execution of a million-dollar NFT scheme through wire fraud.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The European Commission announced in July 2022 that it was planning to draw up regulations to combat money laundering by 2024.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Several blockchains have added support for NFTs since Ethereum created its ERC-721 standard.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] ERC-721 is an "inheritable" smart contract standard, which means that developers can create contracts by copying from a reference implementation.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] ERC-721 provides core methods that allow tracking the owner of a unique identifier, as well as a way for the owner to transfer the asset to others.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Another standard, ERC-1155, offers "semi-fungibility" whereby a token represents a class of interchangeable assets.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] It has become well known that an NFT image can be copied or saved from a web browser by using a right click menu to download the referenced image.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFT supporters disparage this duplication of NFT artwork as a "right-clicker mentality".
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] One collector quoted by *Vice* compared the value of a purchased NFT (in contrast to an unpurchased copy of the underlying asset) to that of a status symbol "to show off that they can afford to pay that much".
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The "right-clicker mentality" phrase spread virally after its introduction, particularly among those who were critical of the NFT marketplace and who appropriated the term to flaunt their ability to capture digital art backed by NFT with ease.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] This criticism was promoted by Australian programmer Geoffrey Huntley who created "The NFT Bay", modeled after The Pirate Bay.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The NFT Bay advertised a torrent file purported to contain 19 terabytes of digital art NFT images.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Huntley compared his work to an art project from Pauline Pantsdown and hoped the site would help educate users on what NFTs are and are not.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The ease of copying NFT content highlights broader legal challenges related to "tokenization," the process by which NFTs purport to represent ownership of underlying assets.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Prior to recent legal reforms, such as the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) in the United States, tokenization faced significant hurdles under traditional property law.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Legal scholars have noted that NFTs did not inherently embody ownership rights enforceable against third parties, as the blockchain record alone does not align with established legal frameworks for property.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] For example, if an NFT claims to represent ownership of digital art, but the art is transferred separately to another party, the NFT holder may lack a legal basis to reclaim it, leaving them with only a contractual claim against the issuer rather than a property right in the asset itself.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] This issue stems from the *numerus clausus* principle, a cornerstone of property law that limits the types of property rights to a finite, standardized list recognized by law.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Historically, tokenization mechanisms—like negotiable instruments or bills of lading—required specific legal recognition to function as enforceable representations of rights in underlying assets.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Without such recognition, NFTs struggled to fit within these constraints, as parties could not create new property rights at will.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In the U.S., the UCC's Article 12, introduced in 2022, addresses this by classifying NFTs as "controllable electronic records" (CERs), a new category of personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral with legal clarity.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] This reform enables tokenization under specific conditions, such as when an NFT represents a "controllable account" (e.g., a payment right), provided the underlying debtor agrees to honor the controller of the CER.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] However, for digital art or other assets without such agreements, the disconnect between NFT ownership and enforceable content rights persists, reinforcing the "right-clicker" critique that blockchain ownership does not guarantee control over the underlying file.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFTs that represent digital art generally do not store the associated artwork file on the blockchain due to the large size of such a file and the limited processing speed of blockchains.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Such a token functions like a certificate of ownership, with a web address that points to the piece of art in question; this however makes the art itself vulnerable to link rot.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] NFT purchases and sales have been enabled by the high energy usage, and consequent greenhouse gas emissions, associated with some kinds of blockchain transactions.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Though all forms of Ethereum transactions have had an impact on the environment, the direct impact of these transaction has also depended on the size of the transaction.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The proof-of-work protocol required to regulate and verify blockchain transactions on networks (including Ethereum until 2022) consumes a large amount of electricity.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] There are also conceptual questions, such as whether the carbon footprint estimate for an NFT purchase should incorporate some portion of the ongoing energy demand of the underlying network, or just the marginal impact of that particular purchase.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] An analogy might be the carbon footprint associated with an additional passenger on a given airline flight.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In 2022, Ethereum cut its energy usage by 99.99 percent by switching to proof of stake.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Other approaches to reducing electricity include the use of off-chain transactions as part of minting an NFT.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Some NFT markets have offered the option of buying carbon offsets when making NFT purchases, although the environmental benefits of this have been questioned.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In some instances, NFT artists have decided against selling some of their own work to limit carbon emission contributions.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Sales platforms charge artists and buyers fees for minting, listing, claiming, and secondary sales.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Analysis of NFT markets in March 2021, in the immediate aftermath of Beeple's "Everydays: the First 5000 Days" selling for US$69.3 million, found that most NFT artworks were selling for less than US$200, with a third selling for less than US$100.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Those selling NFTs below $100 were paying platform fees between 72.5% and 157.5% of that amount.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] On average the fees make up 100.5% of the price, meaning that such artists were on average paying more money in fees than they were making in sales.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] There have been cases of artists and creators having their work sold by others as an NFT without permission.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] After the artist Qing Han died in 2020, her identity was assumed by a fraudster and a number of her works became available for purchase as NFTs.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Similarly, a seller posing as Banksy succeeded in selling an NFT supposedly made by the artist for $336,000 in 2021; the seller refunded the money after the case drew media attention.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In January 2022, the first instance of speech synthesis NFT plagiarism and fraud occurred when an NFT company called Voiceverse was discovered to have stolen content from 15.ai, a non-commercial text-to-speech project.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Log files revealed that Voiceverse had generated voice lines of Twilight Sparkle and Rainbow Dash using 15.ai, pitched them up to sound unrecognizable, promoted them as the byproduct of their own technology, and sold them as NFTs without permission.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] When confronted, Voiceverse stated that someone on their marketing team had used the voice without proper attribution.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The developer of 15.ai, who had previously stated their opposition to NFTs a month prior to the incident, responded with a tweet saying "Go fuck yourself," which went viral and gained widespread support.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The anonymity associated with NFTs and the ease with which they can be forged make it difficult to pursue legal action against NFT plagiarists.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In February 2023, artist Mason Rothschild was ordered to pay $133,000 in damages to Hermès by a New York court, after a jury sided with the copyright holder, for his 2021 digital depictions of the brand's Birkin handbag.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Some NFT marketplaces responded to cases of plagiarism by creating "takedown teams" to respond to artist complaints.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The NFT marketplace OpenSea has rules against plagiarism and deepfakes (non-consensual intimate imagery).
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Some artists criticized OpenSea's efforts, saying they are slow to respond to takedown requests and that artists are subject to support scams from users who claim to be representatives of the platform.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Others argue that there is no market incentive for NFT marketplaces to crack down on plagiarism.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In January 2022, it was reported that some NFTs were being exploited by sellers to unknowingly gather users' IP addresses.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The "exploit" works via the off-chain nature of NFT, as the user's computer automatically follows a web address in the NFT to display the content.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] The server at the address can then log the IP address and, in some cases, dynamically alter the returned content to show the result.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] OpenSea has a particular vulnerability to this loophole because it allows HTML files to be linked.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] Critics compare the structure of the NFT market to a pyramid or Ponzi scheme, in which early adopters profit at the expense of those buying in later.
[src:nft-tokens/non-fungible-token] In June 2022, Bill Gates stated his belief that NFTs are "100% based on greater fool theory".
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:nft-tokens/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] A standard interface for contracts that manage multiple token types.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] A single deployed contract may include any combination of fungible tokens, non-fungible tokens or other configurations (e.g., semi-fungible tokens).
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] The idea is simple and seeks to create a smart contract interface that can represent and control any number of fungible and non-fungible token types.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] In this way, the ERC-1155 token can do the same functions as an ERC-20 and ERC-721 token, and even both at the same time.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] It improves the functionality of both the ERC-20 and ERC-721 standards, making it more efficient and correcting obvious implementation errors.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] The ERC-1155 token is described fully in EIP-1155 (opens in a new tab).
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] To better understand this page, we recommend you first read about token standards, ERC-20, and ERC-721.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] The batch transfer works very similar to regular ERC-20 transfers.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] The only difference in ERC-1155 is that we pass the values as an array and we also pass an array of ids.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] Transfer 200 tokens with id 6 from `_from` to `_to`.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] Transfer 5 tokens with id 13 from `_from` to `_to`.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] In ERC-1155 we only have `transferFrom`, no `transfer`.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] To use it like a regular `transfer`, just set the from address to the address that's calling the function.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] The respective ERC-20 `balanceOf` call likewise has its partner function with batch support.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] Even simpler for the balance call, we can retrieve multiple balances in a single call.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] We pass the array of owners, followed by the array of token ids.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] The approvals are slightly different than ERC-20.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] Instead of approving specific amounts, you set an operator to approved or not approved via `setApprovalForAll`.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] Reading the current status can be done via `isApprovedForAll`.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] As you can see, it's an all-or-nothing operation.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] You cannot define how many tokens to approve or even which token class.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] This is intentionally designed with simplicity in mind.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] You can only approve everything for one address.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] Given the EIP-165 (opens in a new tab) support, ERC-1155 supports receive hooks for smart contracts only.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] When the receiving contract returns this value, it is assumed the contract accepts the transfer and knows how to handle the ERC-1155 tokens.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] Great, no more stuck tokens in a contract!
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] When the supply is just one, the token is essentially a non-fungible token (NFT).
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] And as is standard for ERC-721, you can define a metadata URL.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] The URL can be read and modified by clients, see here (opens in a new tab).
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] We've touched on a few safe transfer rules already in the previous explanations.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] 2. length of `_ids` is not the same as length of `_values`.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-1155] 3. any of the balance(s) of the holder(s) for token(s) in `_ids` is lower than the respective amount(s) in `_values` sent to the recipient.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] A Non-Fungible Token (NFT) is used to identify something or someone in a unique way.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] This type of Token is perfect to be used on platforms that offer collectible items, access keys, lottery tickets, numbered seats for concerts and sports matches, etc.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] This special type of Token has amazing possibilities so it deserves a proper Standard, the ERC-721 came to solve that!
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] The ERC-721 introduces a standard for NFT, in other words, this type of Token is unique and can have different value than another Token from the same Smart Contract, maybe due to its age, rarity or even something else like its visual.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] All NFTs have a `uint256` variable called `tokenId`, so for any ERC-721 Contract, the pair `contract address, uint256 tokenId` must be globally unique.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] That said, a dapp can have a "converter" that uses the `tokenId` as input and outputs an image of something cool, like zombies, weapons, skills or amazing kitties!
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] The ERC-721 (Ethereum Request for Comments 721), proposed by William Entriken, Dieter Shirley, Jacob Evans, Nastassia Sachs in January 2018, is a Non-Fungible Token Standard that implements an API for tokens within Smart Contracts.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] It provides functionalities like to transfer tokens from one account to another, to get the current token balance of an account, to get the owner of a specific token and also the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] Besides these it also has some other functionalities like to approve that an amount of token from an account can be moved by a third party account.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] If a Smart Contract implements the following methods and events it can be called an ERC-721 Non-Fungible Token Contract and, once deployed, it will be responsible to keep track of the created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] Let's see how a Standard is so important to make things simple for us to inspect any ERC-721 Token Contract on Ethereum.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] We just need the Contract Application Binary Interface (ABI) to create an interface to any ERC-721 Token.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] As you can see below we will use a simplified ABI, to make it a low friction example.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] CryptoKitties Contract has some interesting Events other than the Standard ones.
[src:nft-tokens/tokens-erc-721] Let's check two of them, `Pregnant` and `Birth`.
